If I am being very honest , I am very dissatisfied and very unpleased with the Workers Compensation process. This system took a person like myself , someone who was financially okay , and because of relying on this process has caused me to start falling into financial ruin. All this time has gone by and still waiting for my appeal hearing due to my employer contesting it for lost wages. This system is flawed and causes people who have some savings to go into a financial spiral downwards. This process needs to be expedited much much more quickly and this system needs to find a way to get payment to claimant much quicker. It is because of doing the right thing and making a claim that caused everything to begin going downhill. I understand due process and I understand that things have to be investigated and fact checked , however this time period is unacceptable just for a resolution of lost wages and temporary total compensation. If I'm going to be 100 percent honest , I am very let down by this WC program and never again will I make a claim for any injury I may/might/possibly encounter in the future. In my opinion , there should be an updated law making it where things are much more sped up and quicker for both claimant and employer. My last grief is this - during this time in which a person is taken off work and in an appeal process , it isn't very wise for someone to continuously rack up bills for doctors , therapists , and what not if an appeal is no certainty or guarantee that a person who was allowed WC will be awarded WC after a hearing. This process and how lackingly slow it is , in my opinion , is the reason why a majority of workers do not bother with making claims for a work related injury.

What I know is I went to work fine.  I have a job that can be very physical.  While doing the job I was injured.  Nothing has been right since.  The BWC system needs overhauled.  It allowed a bad provider to look at an MRI without ever seeing the patient.  It allowed for a determination of an injury without a history or assessment to be done.  It allowed for documentation based on those assumptions.  It allowed for those assumptions to become record with no way for them to be corrected.  The ED that treated on the DOI billed for treatment not provided.  There is no way to correct this.  How many dollars are wasted on things like that? The injured employee should be presumed innocent until you prove fraud. Your system needs checks and balances.  It needs to be set up to receive complaints about the MCOs and incompetent providers. Now I have heard form Sedgwick's representatives far more than the bwc claim specialist and they are some of the hardest people on earth to deal with. I question their honesty, as the info they say they receive from my doctor and the information he communicated to me in person at visits are polar opposites. For example, Sedgwick called wants me to do occupational therapy, my doctor tells me he doesn't see any sense in this as I have a job in a highly specialized field to return to and he believes I will be able.once I recover. The Sedgwick rep the same day tells me she spoke to my doctor and he wants me to do the therapy, I know for a fact he saw no reason as we talked at length about it that very day just prior to the call with Sedgwick. I feel that the Sedgwick staff only care about getting the injured worker off of comp, regardless of their actual condition. They are difficult to communicate with, ignore what the worker has to say, and are aggressive and overbearing, their only concern is clearly the length of time the worker has been off recovering and not the effectiveness of the recovery or the actual condition of the injured worker. In my case, I was electrocuted with 480v, continue to have lower back pain, ceaseless leg spasms and my neurologist says it will just take time, and no way to tell how long. The Sedgwick rep could clearly care less about that, almost as if the physical recovery process is far down their list of concerns. It has gotten to the point that I am going to involve my attorney in any Sedgwick correspondence going forward. Clearly they are more concerned with revenue than injured workers.

Please note that the following statements are written by someone who is not only in considerable discomfort, but also extremely irritated. Everything about this claim, in my estimation, is complete and unmitigated bullshit. I am not nearly physically fit to go back to work for some time, yet because the treating physician stipulated that I'm ready for light duty as of 3/17 (even while still wearing a cast), I've been working since 4/11. Are you kidding me with this nonsense? I could not have been more clear as I explained to the doctor that mine is a very physical job. I was cleared to go back to work, but with all of the restrictions cited on the Medco form, I can't do anything that I used to do. How in the fuck am I supposed to subsist with no money coming in? Injured workers should rightfully be briefed up front that they may want to apply for a loan, contact the local metropolitan housing authority, and find a nearby soup kitchen or bread line. In this way, the IW can focus on recovery rather than stressing over whether or not there's money for food, rent, utilities, etc. This experience was analogous to siege warfare as far as I'm concerned. With no income for over two months, I was left with no other recourse but to return to work entirely ill-prepared and unhealed. This whole experience has been, and continues to be, absolutely fucked up! Needless to say, I am entirely dissatisfied with this whole mess.

I am in excellent standing with the Board of Nursing and have been all of my career. Until the injury, I did NOT know I had any back issue.
